Rising sea levels combined with increased wave heights and more
intense surges will put all of Ireland's coastal areas at risk of coastal
erosion, northeastern and southwestern coasts in particular.
Amongst others, this will have implications for infrastructure located
Increasing sea levels combined with increased wave heights and storm
surge intensity will put Ireland's coastal infrastructure at risk and this includes
Ireland's major cities. In addition, due to increased levels of winter
precipitation, when combined with increased levels of river flow, innundation
of Ireland's major cities is of particular,concern.
Increased levels of winter precipitation will result in an increased
risk of inland flooding with new areas, previously not subject to
Decreased levels of summer precipitation, particularly in the south
and south east, may result in the increased occurrence of drought
conditions. This will put water supply at risk due to low flows and
Increasing temperatures will serve to prolong the growing season with spring
occuring earlier. Increasing temperatures may also serve to increase yields.
However, this increase may be offset by decreased levels of water availability
Projected shifts in climate and sea level rise will impact upon
the geographical range and phenology (timing of lifecycle
events) of species native to Ireland, resulting in biodiversity
and ecosystem loss. In addition, the occurence of invasive
species is expected to increase under projected climate change.
